  "prompt": "What is the song meaning of Hotel California?",
  "response": "The Eagles' song \"Hotel California\" is widely interpreted as an allegory about the excess and hedonism of the American music and entertainment industry in the 1970s, particularly in California. The song explores themes of materialism, spiritual emptiness, and the seductive but ultimately destructive nature of fame and wealth.\n\nSome key interpretations include:\n\n1. A metaphorical commentary on the darker side of the American Dream, where luxury and success can trap people in a cycle of superficial pleasure\n\n2. A critique of the hedonistic lifestyle of Southern California during the 1970s, with its focus on consumption and self-indulgence\n\n3. An exploration of the music industry's allure, where artists can become metaphorically \"imprisoned\" by their own success\n\nThe lyrics suggest a journey into a place that seems welcoming at first but gradually reveals itself as a kind of spiritual prison, where escape becomes impossible. The song uses vivid imagery to convey a sense of being lured into a beautiful but ultimately hollow existence.\n\nDon Henley, one of the band members, has described the song as their \"interpretation of the high life in Los Angeles,\" highlighting the theme of a glamorous surface concealing a more troubling reality.",
